---
Title: Comments And Optionals
Optionals: answers directions
---

# Comments and optionals

Almost every authoring system has prose that you do *not* want in the final
document: a reminder to yourself, a passage you have cut but are not ready to
delete, an aside that is true but off-topic. Standard Markdown has no syntax for
this — the closest you can do is wrap text in an HTML comment, which is awkward
across multiple paragraphs and useless when you are targeting LaTeX. JMarkdown
fills the gap with two related facilities:

- **Comments** — text that is hidden by default but that you can switch back on
  without deleting it. There is a block form (the `comment` environment) for
  whole passages and an inline form (a `%`-to-end-of-line marker, TeX-style) for
  trailing notes.
- **Optionals** — *named* hide-able regions that you declare once in the
  metadata header and can flip on or off as a group. The motivating case is a
  worksheet whose answers are present in the source but emitted only when you
  ask for the answer key.

Both rest on a single underlying behaviour: a *named region whose content is
emitted only when its `include` flag is true*. A comment is just an optional
named `comment` whose default is "off"; an optional you declare is the same
mechanism under a name of your choosing. Understanding that one idea makes the
whole page fall into place, so we lead with it.

(Throughout, the live demos show the source on the left and its rendered result
on the right, so the examples can never drift from what JMarkdown actually does.)

## Block comments

The `comment` environment is built in — it is always available, with no
declaration or import. Anything inside it is dropped from the output:

```markdown
:::comment
All of this text will be ignored.

And the comment can span multiple blocks.
:::
```

It is genuinely multi-block: paragraphs, lists, headings, and even other
environments inside it all vanish together, which is what makes it suitable for
parking large passages you may want back later. When that day comes, you do not
have to hunt for the closing marker and unwrap anything — you flip one
attribute:

```markdown
:::comment{include=true}
All of this text will now be included in the output.

And the comment can span multiple blocks.
:::
```

`{include=true}` says "emit this region after all"; with it, the body is
processed and rendered exactly as ordinary prose. (`{include=false}` is the
default and is accepted explicitly if you like to be unambiguous.) That single
toggle is the whole comment/optional model: hidden by default, shown on request.

### The `@begin … @end` form

Every comment region has an equivalent spelling as a [block
environment](block-environments.html). The named-block form

```
@begin(comment)
…hidden text…
@end(comment)
```

behaves identically to the colon-delimited `comment` directive — same default
(hidden), same `{include=true}` toggle. Use whichever you prefer; the two are
interchangeable.

The named-block form is often the more comfortable one when a comment lives
*inside* another container, because the closer names what it closes and so does
not depend on counting colons. Here is a live demonstration — the first comment
is hidden, the second carries `{include=true}` and so appears in the output on
the right:

:::markdown-demo
Visible before the notes.

@begin(comment)
A private reminder to myself — hidden by default, so it
does not appear.
@end(comment)

@begin(comment){include=true}
This note carries `include=true`, so it *is* rendered on the right.
@end(comment)

Visible after the notes.
:::

The directive form produces exactly the same result. (Note the colon counting:
the outer `markdown-demo` container uses *more* colons than the `comment`
directive inside it — five against three — because colon-delimited containers
nest by colon count. This is precisely the bookkeeping the `@begin … @end` form
lets you skip.)

:::::markdown-demo
Visible before the notes.

:::comment
Hidden by default — a private reminder that does not appear.
:::

:::comment{include=true}
Shown, because `include=true`.
:::

Visible after the notes.
:::::

## Inline comments

For a short note at the end of a line — too small to be worth a whole
environment — JMarkdown provides an inline comment marker. By default it is the
`%` character, exactly as in TeX: everything from the marker to the end of the
line is removed.

:::markdown-demo
This sentence is visible. %but this trailing note is stripped from the output
The next line continues normally.
:::

The comment does not vanish without a trace: it is replaced by an HTML comment,
so the rendered page contains `<!-- Markdown source commented out -->` where the
note used to be. That marker is invisible in the browser but visible if you view
source — a deliberate, low-noise breadcrumb that *something* was elided here.

### Choosing and preserving the comment text

The inline marker is configured through the `Inline comment` metadata key, whose
value is the marker character optionally followed by a boolean:

```
Inline comment: <character> [true|false]
```

- The **character** sets the marker. Any single character (or short string)
  works; regex metacharacters such as `*` or `(` are handled safely, so you are
  free to pick `#` or `;;` if `%` clashes with your prose.
- The **boolean** (default `false`) controls whether the comment *text* is kept.
  With `false`, the note is replaced by the generic
  `<!-- Markdown source commented out -->` placeholder shown above. With `true`,
  the actual text is preserved inside the HTML comment, so the source
  `Visible %hidden note` renders as `Visible <!-- hidden note -->` — handy when
  the comments are review notes you want to read in the page source.

For example, `Inline comment: ## true` makes `##` the marker *and* preserves the
commented text in the output. If the key is absent, JMarkdown behaves as though
you had written `Inline comment: % false`.

### A note on `%` and mathematics

Because `%` is the TeX comment character and JMarkdown treats it the same way,
take care if your prose contains literal percent signs — `50% off` would lose
everything after the `%`. Two facts soften this:

- Inside math, `%` is safe. Math spans such as `$50\%$` are passed through
  untouched, so the marker only fires in ordinary prose.
- If your text uses percent signs heavily, change the marker to something you
  never type at the start of a comment (for instance `Inline comment: ;;`).

## Optionals

The `comment` environment is for text you are hiding *because it is a comment*.
Often, though, you want to mark a region for conditional inclusion for reasons
that have nothing to do with commenting — the classic case being the answers in
a problem set, which live in the same source as the questions but should appear
only in the instructor's copy. **Optionals** are named, declarable comment
regions built for exactly this.

You declare them once, in the metadata header, as a space-separated list of
names:

```
Optionals: answers directions
```

Each name becomes a hide-able region usable both as a colon-delimited container
directive and as a named block environment, with the same `{include=true}`
toggle as a comment. The two spellings for a declared `answers` optional are:

```markdown
:::answers
…answer text…
:::
```

```
@begin(answers)
…answer text…
@end(answers)
```

By default every optional is **not included** — declaring `answers` gives you a
region that is hidden unless asked for, just like a comment but under a name that
documents its purpose.

### Default state and the `[true]` suffix

If a particular optional should default to *being shown*, put `[true]` after its
name. You can mix defaults freely:

```
Optionals: answers directions[true] hints
```

Here `directions` are shown by default while `answers` and `hints` are hidden.
For symmetry you may write `[false]` explicitly (`answers[false]`); it is the
default and changes nothing, but it can make intent clear in a long list.

### Using a declared optional

Once declared, an optional region is written like any other hide-able
environment. This page declares `Optionals: answers directions` in its own
header, so the demo below is live — `answers` defaults to hidden, and you can see
that the answer region is correctly absent from the rendered output on the
right:

:::::::markdown-demo
::::my-quiz
1. What is the answer to this question?
   :::answers
   *Answer.* I don't know.
   :::

2. What is the answer to this harder question?
   :::answers
   *Answer.* I still don't know — why are you asking me?
   :::

3. Write your thoughts about this exam.
::::
:::::::

The `my-quiz` and `answers` names render as custom elements (`<my-quiz>`,
`<answers>`) — that is the generic behaviour of colon-delimited containers, and
you supply the matching CSS. The point here is the visibility: the three
`answers` regions are present in the source but suppressed in the output because
the optional defaults to off.

To produce the answer key, you do **not** edit the body at all. You change one
line in the header so the optional defaults to shown:

```
Optionals: answers[true] directions
```

With that single edit, every `answers` region across the whole document is
emitted, and the same source now renders the worked answers inline. (You can
still override an individual region the other way with an explicit
`{include=true}` or `{include=false}` on that one block.)

### Project- and global-level optionals

The metadata header is per file. If the same set of optionals applies across a
whole project — every chapter of a book, say — set them once in a project or
global `.jmarkdown/config.json` under the `Optionals` key rather than repeating
the header line in every file. The header value, when present, takes precedence,
following JMarkdown's usual configuration layering (see
[Configuration files](configuration-files.html)).

> [!TIP]
> If you find yourself using an optional heavily — wrapping every answer in an
> `answers` region and hand-typing "*Answer.*" each time — consider promoting it to a
> custom directive instead of an `Optionals` entry. A directive of your own can
> generate the "*Answer.*" lead-in automatically, so the body of each region is
> just the answer text. See [Simple extensions](extensions-simple.html) and
> [Complex extensions](extensions-complex.html) for how to write one.

## Reference

### Block comment syntax

| Form | Effect |
|---|---|
| `:::comment … :::` | Hide the enclosed blocks (default). |
| `:::comment{include=true} … :::` | Emit the enclosed blocks. |
| `@begin(comment) … @end(comment)` | Named-block equivalent; hidden by default. |
| `@begin(comment){include=true} … @end(comment)` | Named-block equivalent; emitted. |

Colon-delimited containers nest by colon count: a `comment` placed inside
another container must use *fewer* colons than its enclosing container (3 for the
inner, 5 or more for the outer, and so on). The `@begin … @end` form nests by
name and needs no counting.

### Inline comment syntax

| Metadata line | Marker | Comment text in output |
|---|---|---|
| *(none)* | `%` | replaced by `<!-- Markdown source commented out -->` |
| `Inline comment: #` | `#` | replaced by the generic placeholder |
| `Inline comment: % true` | `%` | preserved as `<!-- the actual text -->` |
| `Inline comment: ;; false` | `;;` | replaced by the generic placeholder |

The marker hides from its first occurrence on a line to the end of that line.
Markers inside math spans are not treated as comments.

### Optionals

| Header form | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `Optionals: answers` | Declare `answers`; default hidden. |
| `Optionals: answers[true]` | Declare `answers`; default shown. |
| `Optionals: answers[false]` | Declare `answers`; default hidden (explicit). |
| `Optionals: a b c` | Declare several at once, space-separated. |

Each declared name is available in every form a comment is, substituting the
name for `comment`:

```
:::name … :::            (container directive; 3 to 8 colons for nesting)
@begin(name) … @end(name)   (named block environment)
```

Every region honours an explicit `{include=true}` or `{include=false}` that
overrides the declared default for that one block.

